Remsen, July, 1865
My dear cousin Lizzie
What a commotion was
made when Uncle Nathaniel's good letter, and
your representative dropped in among us, you 
ought to have seen it! I was ironing at the 
time, and though I gave myself great credit
for not leaving my work to answer your note
immediately, I must confess that some wrinkles 
dried into the clothes, as every now and then they
were left spread out on the table, while I stole 
away to get a fresh peep at your sweet face.
Each of us girls tried to claim you as a 
nearer relative than the rest by saying "I believe
she looks like me." "No, she don't, she looks like
me" etc. but Lizzie, I carried the palm, for
when we showed the likeness to baby, he said it

speak the truth. Quite a number of our friends
have said that you resemble Jennie, but
cousin Alexander had the good sense to remark
that you looked some like me. I 
thanked him, and said I could get 
many to say so, and he replied that you 
certainly did. A doubtful compliment to yourself I am
afraid you will think, when you have
seen my face, but console yourself with 
the thought that "resemblance and beauty
are not always coincident."
Indeed, dear cousin, I thank you very
much for your photograph, and gladly concede
to your wish and return you mine.
I also send you one of Eddie's, your father's 
namesake. Will you not write to him some 
time, but don't tell him I asked you to, let
him think his likeness brought it. He
left it, when he was home, for you, so you
see it is his gift, not mine. He says he will 
never be illustrious as a letter writer, indeed
he has such a modest estimate of his abilities

in that line, that there is no danger of his beginning
a correspondence, but I know he would
prize a letter, and I think he would answer it.
We think Uncle's and cousins' photographs
very good indeed. I was not home when 
Mr. Thomas brought them, so I did not 
see the commotion they made, but they
were shown me the very first thing when
I arrived. We study the features very often, 
and are fast getting acquainted, but dear
me, I cannot feel satisfied with just seeing
your portraits, I want to see and know
you all. This world does seem to me
most inconveniently large.
I must tell you what a time I had trying
to see Rev. J. Thomas Ligerpool?. I was very
anxious to see him because he had brought
over the cartes from Uncle N's and I thought he would
tell us something about you all.
Eddie and I went to attend the anniversaries
at Whitestown Sem. where brother
Butter used to teach. I staid awhile to

visit a friend, and in that way missed
hearing him and Rev. C. Jones when they 
were in our neighborhood. I intended
however to stop at a place called Bathania?
on my way home, as they were to attend
a Quarterly meeting held there on the day 
I had fixed upon for my return. I was coming
through Utica, and stopped to make same
? hall an hour for the [H.W.] train.
purchases till it was high
time to ? to the depot, as I was going
hurrying down the street I missed a
parcel, and knew must have left at
a music store several ? above. After I searched 
?? and found it then started again for the depot as nearly on
a run as I dared to get comfortable in a city but despite
my haste had the pleasure of seeing the
cars move off when I was within a stone's
throw of the track. Father told me once when

are good for us." That I was not philosophical

Osawatomie, Dec. 6, 1890.
My dear Sister,
We saw yesterday in the Boonville Herald a notice of the death of Johnny Williams - two our of that household have passed away since we left home! How many vacant places will we find it ever we go home! How quickly life passes! Let us live to win heaven!
We are having the grip of winter hold of us! tho' no snow or rain since those dreary days before thanksgiving. Yesterday, John had a last unclear calf killed and we have meat a plenty and very nice. Most of it hangs high in the corn crib, we hope not to be obliged to corn much of it as the weather is cold. You probably know that Robbie intends coming here early in Feb. to rend John's farm or to work for him. John has too much care now that his eyesight has failed so much, tho' he is doing better with his

dairy than ever before. Mary helps him so faithfully, but it is a tax on her she does not find a light one. She drives the team of houses to and from town and they are of the pulling kind giving her arms full exercise I think they are better of that since she has tried less tension on her end of the lines!
That box came so quickly that we can hardly realize that its journey was no less than those other tantalizing ones! John paid for it and the clothes will more than repay him. My water proof dress will I hope be a treasure by and by, if the unclear don't get it first. We have caught four with a trap in the corner they have gnawed through from the outside. The men have been shelling corn and filling the bags for John to go to the mill after feed. He has it exchanged for meal to save him waiting. It takes quite a little while to weigh the corn then its equivalent in ground corn so that Mary usually utilizes it making a call on Mrs. Hovey?. It was from her that I bought the turkey eggs and she will let us have more next spring so we need not keep turkeys all winter.

We shall be glad to get the details of how our farm is rented when it is convenient. What privilege are reserved. If Libbie & Mary Anna are here we may go home next summer - or Mary may
Shall we have half of the apples? Have you made any arrangement to have the roofs cleared in case of heavy snow? Was the water let down in the cistern pump? Is the cellar banked? Have you seen cousin Minnie Roberts since going to Utica? Is she is Omaha now? Is her brother studying medicine? or has he been? If I remember rightly he chose that for his profession before he went to the Academy. I wonder if we shall see Minnie sometime in this western world! What kind of a time had gone in N.Y. Mills? How near do the cars come to 89 Garden St.? You must have enjoyed that floral treat with cousin Mary. I miss the flowers so much. What did you do with our plants at home? We have some here - we have no warm window and I believe we neglected to water the two we hung from hooks near our west window. they dried up and cannot be coaxed to start again. - Well, how are you unclear city

life? Is it quiet there? is cousin Lewis at home? I think you mentioned his working somewhere lately. Is Minnie the youngest daughter? and has she any special friend likely to carry her off the way her sisters have gone?
Mary has been reading over my letter and says it sounds tired - I must not inflict any more upon you. I have a cold am apt to cough mornings - so today I wrote about 4 - unclear and now I sleepy - With love J. [[unclear[[ H. Everett.
